text.title: Wosets are Isomorphic to Each Other or Initial Segments/Proof Without Using Choice
text.summary1: (human1) This mathematical proof shows that two wosets S and T, ordered sets with a well-ordering, must be order isomorphic to each other, or else one set is order isomorphic to an initial segment of the other, trivially if they contain less than two elements, and otherwise provably using a relation ⪯, which is shown to be a reflexive, transitive and antisymmetric total well-ordering.
text.summary2: (claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022) This proof establishes that two well-ordered sets S and T with at least two elements each can be combined into a single well-ordered set U by defining a specific relation that preserves the ordering properties and leads to an order isomorphism between T and either U or an initial segment of U.
text.summary3: (gpt4o) This proof establishes that by defining a specific ordering relation on the union of two well-ordered sets, S and T, a well-ordering can be achieved, and further demonstrates the existence of a strictly increasing mapping from T to U, leading to order isomorphisms either between T and S or vice versa, depending on specific initial conditions.
text.summary4: (Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct) The proof shows that ⪯ is a well-ordering on the disjoint union of sets S and T, establishing a well-ordering on the union of a well-ordered set and an ordered set.
text.summary5: (Qwen2.5-3B-Instruct) The proof demonstrates that a well-ordering can be established on the union of ordered sets S and T, and that this order is order-isomorphic to subsets of S or T, depending on the smallest element’s location.
